item.title: U.K. Suspends Extradition Treaty With Hong Kong
item.description: The British government said it would suspend its extradition treaty with Hong Kong in response to China’s decision to impose a new security law on the former British colony, the latest sign of deteriorating diplomatic relations between Western nations and China.

item.title: Tokyo Olympics Organizers Seek to Save Endangered Games
item.description: Organizers for the Tokyo Olympics are making health and safety plans for a pandemic-era Games that they still can’t ensure will take place next year, including the possibility that any spectators would be required to show proof they aren’t infected with coronavirus.

item.title: Saudi Arabia's Aging King Salman Admitted to Hospital for Checks
item.description: King Salman entered a hospital in the kingdom’s capital after suffering from gallbladder inflammation, reigniting speculation about succession plans for his son and heir apparent.

item.title: China Snuffs Out One Covid-19 Cluster, Wages War on Another
item.description: China says it has ended a coronavirus outbreak in Beijing that it has been battling since mid-June, even as it deployed its so-called “wartime mode” measures to a new cluster in the country’s remote northwest.

item.title: How Europe Slowed Its Coronavirus Cases From a Torrent to a Trickle
item.description: Even as a surge in cases forces a number of U.S. states to reimpose restrictions, Europe’s reopening is for the most part going according to plan. Experts put that down to changing patterns of behavior and an understanding that this isn’t a “nothing crisis.”

item.title: Bone-Dry Australia Faces Backlash Against Dam Projects
item.description: Australia’s plans for dam projects are angering some indigenous groups and alarming environmental activists who argue the dams will harm ecosystems and disturb cultural sites.
